ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Long, Minh, Muoi, Phan, Phat, Vinh, Cuong, Hien, Hoa, Lam, Lan.  Chinese Wing, Chi, Kin, Cheuk, Chi Wai, Chuen, Hon, Keung, Wah, Wai, Chiu, Ho.","Chinese: alternative Mandarin form of the surname 敖, see   Ao  .","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surnames 歐 and 區, see   Ou   1 and 2."],"variants":[{"name":"Auerbach","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Moshe, Emanuel, Isidor, Bronia, Chaim, Faigy, Menachem, Meyer, Yechezkel.","German: habitational name from any of several places in southern Germany and Austria called Auerbach ‘the stream at the water meadow’. See also 2,   Au  , and   Bach  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from the town of Auerbach in the Upper Palatinate, Bavaria. Compare   Averbach  ."]},{"name":"Ao","meanings":["Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 敖, meaning both ‘rambling’ and ‘deposed king without posthumous titles’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from the personal name of <i>Tai Ao</i> (太敖), teacher of the legendary king Zhuanxu (traditional dates: 2514–2437  BC ). (ii) it is said that the surname is also borne by descendants of deposed kings of the former state of Chu, with no posthumous titles, during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC )."]},{"name":"Auer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alois, Hans, Erwin, Matthias, Siegfried, Bernd, Bernhard, Erna, Franz, Fritz, Hermann, Horst.","German (mainly Bavaria): topographic name for someone living by a water meadow, German <i>Au</i>, or a habitational name for someone from a place called Au or Aue (see   Au   and   Aue  ). This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), Czechia, and Slovenia."]}]},{"name":"Merfyn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: from Old Welsh <i>mer</i>, probably meaning ‘marrow’ + <i>myn</i> ‘eminent’; borne by a shadowy 9th-century Welsh king."],"variants":[{"name":"Mervin","meanings":["Anglicized form of Welsh Merfyn , now also widely used outside Wales."]},{"name":"Mervyn","meanings":["Anglicized form of Welsh Merfyn , now also widely used outside Wales."]}]},{"name":"\"Frych","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German and Swiss German: nickname from Middle High German <i>vrech</i> ‘eager, bold, brave’."],"variants":[{"name":"Freck","meanings":["North German: variant of   Frech  ."]}]},{"name":"the","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Either a variant spelling of   Ty   or a transferred use of the surname, a local name for someone who lived by a common pasture, Middle English <i>tye</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Merfyn \"Frych the Freckled\" ap Gwriad was born in 0795, in Caernarfonshire, Wales, his father, Gwriad ab Elidir Prince of Deheubarth King of Manaw, was 40 and his mother, Ethyllt Ferch Cynan, was 25. He had at least 1 son with Queen Nest ferch Cadell. He died about 0844, in Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 50, and was buried in Wales."},"et":{"0795–Abt 844":"0795–umbes 0844","0790–0850":"0790–0850","0795–0844":"0795–0844","0770–0825":"0770–0825","0820–0878":"0820–0878","0755–0825":"0755–0825","0770–Female":"0770–Surnud","from 825 to 844":"0825 kuni 0844","0790":"0790","Abt 844":"umbes 0844","0820":"0820","0755":"0755","about 0825":"umbes 0825","about 0820":"umbes 0820","0795":"0795","0850":"0850","0770":"0770","825":"0825","0825":"0825","0844":"0844","0878":"0878","Cyfeiliog, Ketell, Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales","Deheubarth, Wales":"West Wales, Wales, United Kingdom","of Caer Seiont, Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales","Anglesey, Wales":"Anglesey, Wales, Uni